<ns450:section xmlns:ns450="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.j2ee.ejb.client.webServicesClients.overview">

  <ns451:title xmlns:ns451="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Web services clients</ns451:title>
  <ns452:para xmlns:ns452="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    The EJB specification requires that compliant application servers
    support JAX-RPC and hence web services clients.
  </ns452:para>
  <ns453:para xmlns:ns453="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    Web services clients request bean services using SOAP 
    <ns454:emphasis xmlns:ns454="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Simple Object Access Protocol</ns454:emphasis>.
    These SOAP/XML service requests are typically sent via 
    HTTP/TCP/IP. Java provides JAX-RPC, the <ns455:emphasis xmlns:ns455="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Java
    API for XML-based Remote Procedure Call</ns455:emphasis>
    for processing SOAP service requests. 
  </ns453:para>
  <ns456:para xmlns:ns456="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    JAX-RPC provides
    a servlet which does the de-marshaling of the SOAP/XML/HTTP
    service request and delegates its realization to the enterprise
    bean which acts as JAX-RPC servant.
  </ns456:para>
</ns450:section>